# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andré-géraud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:andré-géraud/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:andré-géraud/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:andré-géraud/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:andré-géraud/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:andré-géraud/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:andré-géraud/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:andré-géraud/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:andré-géraud/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:andré-géraud/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:andré-géraud/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:andré-géraud/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:andré-géraud/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] Géraud studied history at Bordeaux University and in 1905 joined the Landon Bureau of *L'Écho de Paris*.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] Three years later, he became its chief British correspondent.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] He wrote on international affairs for *The Pall Mall Gazette* in 1910 and *The Daily Telegraph* in 1912.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] Géraud was an early advocate of animal rights.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] In 1924, he authored *Déclaration des droits de l'animal* which was re-published in 1939.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] Because the book was never translated into English, Géraud is rarely cited in English-language literature relating to animal rights, unlike Henry Stephens Salt, who is often cited.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] The book influenced the creation of the Universal Declaration of Animal Rights by Ligue Française des Droits de l’Animal in 1978.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] The book put forward the idea of an "animal code" based on three guiding principles.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] Animals must be happy, or, they suffer; the suffering inflicted on animals must be strictly indispensable; and the pleasures allowed to animals are justified and must not be deprived.
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] Géraud commented that "the Declaration of Animal Rights in the twentieth century shall be the counterpart of the Declaration of Human Rights in the eighteenth century".
[src:andré-géraud/andré-géraud] After the Fall of France in June 1940, Géraud sailed to the United States on a British destroyer.
